Samothraciam—Lemni: these islanda together with Imbros were the seat of the Oabiric worship, on which see Don. 1. o. p. 164 foll„ Lobeck qu. p. uos—1329, Preller Gr. Hytla 1 660—673. Herodotus 11 51 is the first who mentions the Samothracian mysteries. Preller thinks that these were not of much importanoe till after the Persian War, and that they were partly copied from the Eleusinia. Aristophanes (Pax 278) speaks of the Samothracian initiation as a safeguard in danger; especially at sea, as we learn from other sources, cf. N. D. 111 89.
